# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ffmpeg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ffmpeg/codec] A **codec** is a computer hardware or software component that encodes or decodes a data stream or signal.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] *Codec* is a portmanteau of **coder/decoder**.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] In electronic communications, an **endec** is a device that acts as both an encoder and a decoder on a signal or data stream, and hence is a type of codec.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] *Endec* is a portmanteau of **encoder/decoder**.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] A coder or encoder encodes a data stream or a signal for transmission or storage, possibly in encrypted form, and the decoder function reverses the encoding for playback or editing.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Codecs are used in videoconferencing, streaming media, and video editing applications.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Originally, in the mid-20th century, a codec was a hardware device that coded analog signals into digital form using pulse-code modulation (PCM).
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Later, the term was also applied to software for converting between digital signal formats, including companding functions.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] An audio codec converts analog audio signals into digital signals for transmission or encodes them for storage.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] A receiving device converts the digital signals back to analog form using an audio decoder for playback.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] An example of this is the codecs used in the sound cards of personal computers.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] A video codec accomplishes the same task for video signals.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] When implementing the Infrared Data Association (IrDA) protocol, an endec may be used between the UART and the optoelectronic systems.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Examples of hardware codecs include Intel QSV and Azalia Audio; examples of software codecs include FFmpeg (and its Libavcodec).
[src:ffmpeg/codec] In addition to encoding a signal, a codec may also compress the data to reduce transmission bandwidth or storage space.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Compression codecs are classified primarily into lossy codecs and lossless codecs.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Lossless codecs are often used for archiving data in compressed form while retaining all information present in the original stream.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] If preserving the original quality of the stream is more important than eliminating the correspondingly larger data sizes, lossless codecs are preferred.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Using more than one codec or encoding scheme successively can also degrade quality significantly.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] The decreasing cost of storage capacity and network bandwidth has a tendency to reduce the need for lossy codecs for some media.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] They reduce quality in order to maximize compression.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Often, this type of compression is virtually indistinguishable from the original uncompressed sound or images, depending on the codec and the settings used.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] The most widely used lossy data compression technique in digital media is based on the discrete cosine transform (DCT), used in compression standards such as JPEG images, H.26x and MPEG video, and MP3 and AAC audio.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Smaller data sets ease the strain on relatively expensive storage sub-systems such as non-volatile memory and hard disk, as well as write-once-read-many formats such as CD-ROM, DVD, and Blu-ray Disc.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Lower data rates also reduce cost and improve performance when the data is transmitted, e.g., over the internet.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Two principal techniques are used in codecs, pulse-code modulation and delta modulation.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Codecs are often designed to emphasize certain aspects of the media to be encoded.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] For example, a digital video (using a DV codec) of a sports event needs to encode motion well but not necessarily exact colors, while a video of an art exhibit needs to encode color and surface texture well.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Audio codecs for cell phones need to have very low latency between source encoding and playback.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] In contrast, audio codecs for recording or broadcasting can use high-latency audio compression techniques to achieve higher fidelity at a lower bit rate.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] There are thousands of audio and video codecs, ranging in cost from free to hundreds of dollars or more.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] This variety of codecs can create compatibility and obsolescence issues.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] The impact is lessened for older formats, for which free or nearly-free codecs have existed for a long time.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] The older formats are often ill-suited to modern applications, however, such as playback on small portable devices.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] For example, raw uncompressed PCM audio (44.1 kHz, 16-bit stereo, as represented on an audio CD or in a .wav or .aiff file) has long been a standard across multiple platforms, but its transmission over networks is slow and expensive compared with more modern compressed formats, such as Opus and MP3.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Many multimedia data streams contain both audio and video, and often some metadata that permits synchronization of audio and video.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Each of these three streams may be handled by different programs, processes, or hardware, but for the multimedia data streams to be useful in stored or transmitted form, they must be encapsulated together in a container format.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Lower bitrate codecs allow more users, but they also have more distortion.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Beyond the initial increase in distortion, lower bit rate codecs also achieve their lower bit rates by using more complex algorithms that make certain assumptions, such as those about the media and the packet loss rate.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Other codecs may not make those same assumptions.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] When a user with a low bitrate codec talks to a user with another codec, additional distortion is introduced by each transcoding.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Audio Video Interleave (AVI) is sometimes erroneously described as a codec, but AVI is actually a container format, while a codec is a software or hardware tool that encodes or decodes audio or video into or from some audio or video format.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] Audio and video encoded with many codecs might be put into an AVI container, although AVI is not an ISO standard.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] There are also other well-known container formats, such as Ogg, ASF, QuickTime, RealMedia, Matroska, and DivX Media Format.
[src:ffmpeg/codec] MPEG transport stream, MPEG program stream, MP4, and ISO base media file format are examples of container formats that are ISO standardized.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg also includes other tools: `ffplay`, a simple media player, and `ffprobe`, a command-line tool to display media information.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Among included libraries are libavcodec, an audio/video codec library used by many commercial and free software products, **libavformat** (Lavf), an audio/video container mux and demux library, and libavfilter, a library for enhancing and editing filters through a GStreamer-like filtergraph.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg is part of the workflow of many other software projects, and its libraries are a core part of software media players such as VLC, and has been included in core processing for YouTube and Bilibili.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Encoders and decoders for many audio and video file formats are included, making it highly useful for the transcoding of common and uncommon media files.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg is published under the LGPL-2.1-or-later or GPL-2.0-or-later, depending on which options are enabled.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The project was started by Fabrice Bellard (using the pseudonym "Gérard Lantau") in 2000, and was led by Michael Niedermayer from 2004 until 2015.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Some FFmpeg developers were also part of the MPlayer project.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The "FF" in FFmpeg stands for "fast forward." The logo represents a zigzag scan pattern that shows how MPEG video codecs handle entropy encoding.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] On March 13, 2011, a group of FFmpeg developers decided to fork the project under the name Libav.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The group decided to fork the project due to a disagreement with the leadership of FFmpeg.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] On January 10, 2014, two Google employees announced that over 1000 bugs had been fixed in FFmpeg during the previous two years by means of fuzz testing.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] In January 2018, the *ffserver* command-line program – a long-time component of FFmpeg – was removed.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The developers had previously deprecated the program citing high maintenance efforts due to its use of internal application programming interfaces.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] In April 2026, Anthropic's Claude Mythos Preview found a 16-year-old critical vulnerability in FFmpeg codec H.264.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The project publishes a new release every three months on average.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] While release versions are available from the website for download, FFmpeg developers recommend that users compile the software from source using the latest build from their source code, using the Git version control system.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Two video coding formats with corresponding codecs and one container format have been created within the FFmpeg project so far.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The two video codecs are the lossless FFV1, and the lossless and lossy Snow codec.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Development of Snow has stalled, while its bit-stream format has not been finalized yet, making it experimental since 2011.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The multimedia container format called NUT is no longer being actively developed, but still maintained.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] In summer 2010, FFmpeg developers Fiona Glaser, Ronald Bultje, and David Conrad, announced the ffvp8 decoder.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Through testing, they determined that ffvp8 was faster than Google's own libvpx decoder.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Starting with version 0.6, FFmpeg also supported WebM and VP8.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] In October 2013, a native VP9 decoder and OpenHEVC, an open source High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC) decoder, were added to FFmpeg.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] In 2016 the native AAC encoder was considered stable, removing support for the two external AAC encoders from VisualOn and FAAC.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg 3.0 (nicknamed *"Einstein"*) retained build support for the Fraunhofer FDK AAC encoder.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Since version 3.4 *"Cantor"* FFmpeg supported the FITS image format.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Since November 2018 in version 4.1 *"al-Khwarizmi"* AV1 can be muxed in MP4 and Matroska, including WebM.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg encompasses software implementations of video and audio compressing and decompressing algorithms.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] These can be compiled and run on many different instruction sets, including x86 (IA-32 and x86-64), PPC (PowerPC), ARM, DEC Alpha, SPARC, and MIPS.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] There are a variety of application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) for audio/video compression and decompression.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] These ASICs can partially or completely offload the computation from the host CPU.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Instead of a complete implementation of an algorithm, only the API is required to use such an ASIC.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The following APIs are also supported: DirectX Video Acceleration (DXVA2, Windows), Direct3D 11 (D3D11VA, Windows), Media Foundation (Windows), Vulkan (VKVA), VideoToolbox (iOS, iPadOS, macOS), RockChip MPP, OpenCL, OpenMAX, MMAL (Raspberry Pi), MediaCodec (Android OS), V4L2 (Linux).
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Depending on the environment, these APIs may lead to specific ASICs, to GPGPU routines, or to SIMD CPU code.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg supports many common and some uncommon image formats.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] The **PGMYUV** image format is a homebrew variant of the binary (P5) PGM Netpbm format.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg also supports 16-bit depths of the PGM and PPM formats, and the binary (P7) PAM format with or without alpha channel, depth 8 bit or 16 bit for `pix_fmts` *monob, gray, gray16be, rgb24, rgb48be, ya8, rgba, rgb64be*.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Output formats (container formats and other ways of creating output streams) in FFmpeg are called "muxers".
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] YVU9, YV12, YV16, and YV24 are supported as *rawvideo* codec in FFmpeg.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] UYVY 10bpc without a padding is supported as *bitpacked* codec in FFmpeg.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] UYVY 10bpc with 2-bits padding is supported as *v210* codec in FFmpeg.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] 16bpc (Y216) is supported as *targa_y216* codec in FFmpeg.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg does not support IMC1-IMC4, AI44, CYMK, RGBE, Log RGB and other formats.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] It also does not yet support ARGB 1:5:5:5, 2:10:10:10, or other BMP bitfield formats that are not commonly used.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg supports, among others, the following filters.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg supports the following devices via external libraries.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg contains more than 100 codecs, most of which use compression techniques of one kind or another.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Many such compression techniques may be subject to legal claims relating to software patents.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Such claims may be enforceable in countries like the United States which have implemented software patents, but are considered unenforceable or void in member countries of the European Union, for example.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] Patents for many older codecs, including AC3 and all MPEG-1 and MPEG-2 codecs, have expired.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg is licensed under the LGPL license, but if a particular build of FFmpeg is linked against any GPL libraries (notably x264), then the entire binary is licensed under the GPL.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg is used by software such as Blender, Cinelerra-GG Infinity, HandBrake, Kodi, MPC-HC, Plex, Shotcut, VirtualDub2 (a VirtualDub fork), VLC media player, xine and YouTube.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] It handles video and audio playback in Chromium (and deliveries such as Google Chrome and Microsoft Edge) and the Linux version of Firefox.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] GUI front-ends for FFmpeg have been developed, including Multimedia Xpert, XMedia Recode and ShutterEncoder.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg is used by ffdshow, FFmpegInterop, the GStreamer FFmpeg plug-in, LAV Filters and OpenMAX IL to expand the encoding and decoding capabilities of their respective multimedia platforms.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] As part of NASA's Mars 2020 mission, FFmpeg is used by the Perseverance rover on Mars for image and video compression before footage is sent to Earth.
[src:ffmpeg/ffmpeg] FFmpeg is also being used in embedded applications, where it can be used with custom hardware to simplify version and dependency management and also to provide operating system abstraction across multiple different OS and processor manufacturers.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] libavcodec is an integral part of many open-source multimedia applications and frameworks.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] The popular MPV, xine and VLC media players use it as their main, built-in decoding engine that enables playback of many audio and video formats on all supported platforms.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] It is also used by the ffdshow tryouts decoder as its primary decoding library. libavcodec is also used in video editing and transcoding applications like Avidemux, MEncoder or Kdenlive for both decoding and encoding.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] libavcodec contains decoder and sometimes encoder implementations of several proprietary formats, including ones for which no public specification has been released.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] As such, a significant reverse engineering effort is part of libavcodec development.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] However, while libavcodec does strive to achieve decoding that is bit-exact to their official format implementations, occasional bugs and missing features in such re-implementations can sometimes introduce playback compatibility problems for certain files.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] Libavcodec contains more than 100 codecs, most of which do not just store uncompressed data.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] Most codecs that compress information could be claimed by patent holders.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] Such claims may be enforceable in countries like the United States which have implemented software patents, but are considered unenforceable or void in countries that have not implemented software patents.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] Furthermore, many of these codecs are only released under terms that forbid reverse engineering, even for purposes of interoperability.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] These terms of use are forbidden in certain countries.
[src:ffmpeg/libavcodec] For example, some European Union nations have not implemented software patents and have laws expressly allowing reverse engineering for purposes of interoperability.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] In the analog video world, transcoding can be performed just while files are being searched, as well as for presentation.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] For example, Cineon and DPX files have been widely used as a common format for digital cinema, but the data size of a two-hour movie is about 8 terabytes (TB).
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] That large size can increase the cost and difficulty of handling movie files.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] However, transcoding into a JPEG2000 lossless format has better data compression performance than other lossless coding technologies; in many cases, JPEG2000 can compress images to half their original size.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Transcoding is commonly a lossy process, introducing generation loss; however, transcoding can be lossless if the output is either losslessly compressed or uncompressed.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Transcoding is a two-step process in which the original data is decoded to an intermediate uncompressed format (e.g., PCM for audio; YUV for video), which is then encoded into the target format.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] image), one will generally decode it, edit it, then re-encode it.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] , and make all edits on that copy, rather than repeatedly re-encoding it.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Similarly, if encoding to a lossy format is required, it should be deferred until the data is finalised, e.g., after mastering.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] , but may use an identical sampling rate with higher compression.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] , and is used if the output resolution differs from the resolution of the media.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] One can also use formats with bitrate peeling, which allow one to easily lower the bitrate without re-encoding, but quality is often lower than a re-encode.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] For example, in Vorbis, bitrate peeling as of 2008, the quality is inferior to re-encoding.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] The key drawback of transcoding in lossy formats is decreased quality.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Compression artifacts are cumulative, so transcoding causes a progressive loss of quality with each successive generation, known as digital generation loss.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] For this reason, transcoding (in lossy formats) is generally discouraged unless unavoidable.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] These lossless formats can be transcoded to PCM formats or transcoded directly from one lossless format to another lossless format, without any loss in quality.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] They can be transcoded into a lossy format, but these copies will then not be able to be transcoded into another format of any kind (PCM, lossless, or lossy) without a subsequent loss of quality.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] For image editing users are advised to capture or save images in a raw or uncompressed format, and then edit a copy of that master version, only converting to lossy formats if smaller file sized images are needed for final distribution.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] As with audio, transcoding from lossy format to another format of any type will result in a loss of quality.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] For video editing, (for video converting), images are normally compressed directly during the recording process due to the huge file sizes that would be created if they were not, and because the huge storage demands being too cumbersome for the user otherwise.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Although transcoding can be found in many areas of content adaptation, it is commonly used in the area of mobile phone content adaptation.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] In this case, transcoding is a must, due to the diversity of mobile devices and their capabilities.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] This diversity requires an intermediate state of content adaptation in order to make sure that the source content will adequately function on the target device to which it is sent.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Transcoding video from most consumer digital cameras can reduce the file size significantly while keeping the quality about the same.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] This is possible because most consumer cameras are real-time, power-constrained devices having neither the processing power nor the robust power supplies of desktop CPUs.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] One of the most popular technologies in which transcoding is used is the Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS), which is the technology used to send or receive messages with media (image, sound, text and video) between mobile phones.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] For example, when a camera phone is used to take a digital picture, a high-quality image of at least 640 × 480 pixels is created.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] When sending the image to another phone, this high-resolution image might be transcoded to a lower-resolution image with fewer colors in order to better fit the target device's screen size and color limitations.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] This size and color reduction improves the user experience on the target device, and is sometimes the only way for content to be sent between different mobile devices.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Transcoding is extensively used by home theatre PC software to reduce the usage of disk space by video files.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] The most common operation in this application is the transcoding of MPEG-2 files to the MPEG-4 or H.264 format.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Real-time transcoding in a many-to-many way (any input format to any output format) is becoming a necessity to provide true search capability for any multimedia content on any mobile device, with over 500 million videos on the web and a plethora of mobile devices.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] Before the advent of semiconductors and integrated circuits, real-time resolution and frame rate transcoding between different analog video standards was achieved by a CRT/camera tube combination.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] The CRT part does not write onto a phosphor, but onto a thin, dielectric target; the camera part reads the deposited charge pattern at a different scan rate from the back side of this target.
[src:ffmpeg/transcoding] The setup could also be used as a genlock.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] A **video codec** is software or hardware that compresses and decompresses digital video.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] In the context of video compression, *codec* is a portmanteau of *encoder* and *decoder*, while a device that only compresses is typically called an *encoder*, and one that only decompresses is a *decoder*.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The compressed data format usually conforms to a standard video coding format.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The compression is typically lossy, meaning that the compressed video lacks some information present in the original video.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] A consequence of this is that decompressed video has lower quality than the original, uncompressed video because there is insufficient information to accurately reconstruct the original video.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] There are complex relationships between the video quality, the amount of data used to represent the video (determined by the bit rate), the complexity of the encoding and decoding algorithms, sensitivity to data losses and errors, ease of editing, random access, and end-to-end delay (latency).
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Historically, video was stored as an analog signal on magnetic tape.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Around the time when the compact disc entered the market as a digital-format replacement for analog audio, it became feasible to also store and convey video in digital form.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Because of the large amount of storage and bandwidth needed to record and convey raw video, a method was needed to reduce the amount of data used to represent the raw video.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Since then, engineers and mathematicians have developed a number of solutions for achieving this goal that involve compressing the digital video data.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] In 1974, discrete cosine transform (DCT) compression was introduced by Nasir Ahmed, T.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] During the late 1980s, a number of companies began experimenting with DCT lossy compression for video coding, leading to the development of the H.261 standard.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] H.261 was the first practical video coding standard, and was developed by a number of companies, including Hitachi, PictureTel, NTT, BT, and Toshiba, among others.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Since H.261, DCT compression has been adopted by all the major video coding standards that followed.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The most popular video coding standards used for codecs have been the MPEG standards.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] MPEG-1 was developed by the Motion Picture Experts Group (MPEG) in 1991, and it was designed to compress VHS-quality video.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It was succeeded in 1994 by MPEG-2/H.262, which was developed by a number of companies, primarily Sony, Thomson and Mitsubishi Electric.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] MPEG-2 became the standard video format for DVD and SD digital television.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] In 1999, it was followed by MPEG-4/H.263, which was a major leap forward for video compression technology.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It was developed by a number of companies, primarily Mitsubishi Electric, Hitachi and Panasonic.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The most widely used video coding format, as of 2016, is H.264/MPEG-4 AVC.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It was developed in 2003 by a number of organizations, primarily Panasonic, Godo Kaisha IP Bridge and LG Electronics.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] H.264 is the main video encoding standard for Blu-ray Discs, and is widely used by streaming internet services such as YouTube, Netflix, Vimeo, and iTunes Store, web software such as Adobe Flash Player and Microsoft Silverlight, and various HDTV broadcasts over terrestrial and satellite television.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] AVC has been succeeded by HEVC (H.265), developed in 2013.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It is heavily patented, with the majority of patents belonging to Samsung Electronics, GE, NTT and JVC Kenwood.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The adoption of HEVC has been hampered by its complex licensing structure.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] HEVC is, in turn, succeeded by Versatile Video Coding (VVC).
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] There are also the open and free VP8, VP9 and AV1 video coding formats, used by YouTube, all of which were developed with involvement from Google.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Video codecs are used in DVD players, Internet video, video on demand, digital cable, digital terrestrial television, videotelephony and a variety of other applications.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] In particular, they are widely used in applications that record or transmit video, which may not be feasible with the high data volumes and bandwidths of uncompressed video.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] For example, they are used in operating theaters to record surgical operations, in IP cameras in security systems, and in remotely operated underwater vehicles and unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Any video stream or file can be encoded using a wide variety of live video format options.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Video codecs seek to represent a fundamentally analog data set in a digital format.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Because of the design of analog video signals, which represent luminance (luma) and color information (chrominance, chroma) separately, a common first step in image compression in codec design is to represent and store the image in a YCbCr color space.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It is common to represent the ratios of information stored in these different channels in the following way YCbCr.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Different codecs use different chroma subsampling ratios as appropriate to their compression needs.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Video compression schemes for Web and DVD make use of a 4:2:1 color sampling pattern, and the DV standard uses 4:1:1 sampling ratios.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Professional video codecs designed to function at much higher bitrates and to record a greater amount of color information for post-production manipulation, sample in 4:2:2 and 4:4:4 ratios.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Examples of these codecs include Panasonic's DVCPRO50 and DVCPROHD codecs (4:2:2), Sony's HDCAM-SR (4:4:4), Panasonic's HDD5 (4:2:2), Apple's Prores HQ 422 (4:2:2).
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It is also worth noting that video codecs can operate in RGB space as well.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] These codecs tend not to sample the red, green, and blue channels in different ratios, since there is less perceptual motivation for doing so—just the blue channel could be undersampled.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Some amount of spatial and temporal downsampling may also be used to reduce the raw data rate before the basic encoding process.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The most popular encoding transform is the 8x8 DCT.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Codecs that make use of a wavelet transform are also entering the market, especially in camera workflows that involve dealing with RAW image formatting in motion sequences.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] This process involves representing the video image as a set of macroblocks.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] For more information about this critical facet of video codec design, see B-frames.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The output of the transform is first quantized, then entropy encoding is applied to the quantized values.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The entropy coding method typically uses variable-length coding tables.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Some encoders compress the video in a multiple-step process called *n-pass* encoding (e.g.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] 2-pass), which performs a slower but potentially higher quality compression.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The decoding process consists of performing, to the extent possible, an inversion of each stage of the encoding process.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The one stage that cannot be exactly inverted is the quantization stage.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] There, a best-effort approximation of inversion is performed.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] This part of the process is often called *inverse quantization* or *dequantization*, although quantization is an inherently non-invertible process.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Video codec designs are usually standardized or eventually become standardized—i.e., specified precisely in a published document.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] However, only the decoding process need be standardized to enable interoperability.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The encoding process is typically not specified at all in a standard, and implementers are free to design their encoder however they want, as long as the video can be decoded in the specified manner.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] For this reason, the quality of the video produced by decoding the results of different encoders that use the same video codec standard can vary dramatically from one encoder implementation to another.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] A variety of video compression formats can be implemented on PCs and in consumer electronics equipment.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] It is therefore possible for multiple codecs to be available in the same product, reducing the need to choose a single dominant video compression format to achieve interoperability.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Standard video compression formats can be supported by multiple encoder and decoder implementations from multiple sources.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] For example, video encoded with a standard MPEG-4 Part 2 codec such as Xvid can be decoded using any other standard MPEG-4 Part 2 codec such as FFmpeg MPEG-4 or DivX Pro Codec, because they all use the same video format.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Codecs have their qualities and drawbacks.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] The trade-off between compression power, speed, and fidelity (including artifacts) is usually considered the most important figure of technical merit.
[src:ffmpeg/video-codec] Online video material is encoded by a variety of codecs, and this has led to the availability of codec packs — a pre-assembled set of commonly used codecs combined with an installer available as a software package for PCs, such as K-Lite Codec Pack, Perian and Combined Community Codec Pack.
